# ==============================================================================
# StockkAsk Git Exclusion Configuration (.gitignore)
# ==============================================================================
# WHAT IS THIS FILE?
# When you track your project with Git, by default Git wants to track every single 
# file in this directory. A ".gitignore" file tells Git: "Ignore these specific 
# files and directories. Never upload them to my online repository (like GitHub)."
#
# WHY DO WE NEED IT FOR SECURITY?
# In modern development, we keep API keys, passwords, and private tokens inside a 
# file named ".env" (environment secrets). If you upload ".env" to GitHub, malicious 
# bots will find it within minutes, steal your keys (OpenAI, Pinecone), run up massive 
# bills, and access your database. This file acts as our primary shield against leaks.
# ==============================================================================

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 1. ENVIRONMENT & SENSITIVE SECRETS (CRITICAL SECURITY)
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# We exclude all files containing environmental secrets and local configurations.
# Never, under any circumstance, remove these lines.
.env
.env.local
.env.development
.env.production
.env.staging
.env*.local
*.env

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 2. PYTHON VIRTUAL ENVIRONMENTS
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Virtual environments contain the actual Python executable and libraries installed
# via pip. They contain thousands of files and are very large (hundreds of MBs).
# We do not track them because they can be easily re-created using 'requirements.txt'.
venv/
.venv/
env/
ENV/
lib/
lib64/
parts/
sdist/
var/
wheels/
share/python-wheels/
*.egg-info/
.installed.cfg
*.egg
MANIFEST

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 3. PYTHON CACHE AND COMPILED BYTECODE
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Python automatically compiles your source code (.py files) into optimized bytecode 
# (.pyc files) so it runs faster next time. This is machine-generated code and changes 
# constantly. We only want to track our human-written source code.
**/__pycache__/
*.py[cod]
*$py.class

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 4. TESTING AND COVERAGE REPORTING
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# When you run tests, testing frameworks generate logs, cache folders, and coverage reports.
# These are generated dynamically at runtime, so we ignore them.
.pytest_cache/
.tox/
.nox/
.coverage
.coverage.*
.cache
htmlcov/
nosetests.xml
coverage.xml
*.cover
*.log

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 5. INTEGRATED DEVELOPMENT ENVIRONMENT (IDE) & EDITOR SETTINGS
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Different developers use different editors (VS Code, PyCharm, Sublime). Editors 
# create local configuration folders (like Workspace settings). We keep these local 
# because they shouldn't overwrite other developers' preferences.
.vscode/
.idea/
*.suo
*.ntvs*
*.njsproj
*.sln
*.swp
*.swo

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 6. OPERATING SYSTEM JUNKS
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# OS-specific files created by Windows (Thumbs.db) or macOS (.DS_Store) for folder
# thumbnail settings. They are irrelevant to our application code.
.DS_Store
.DS_Store?
ehthumbs.db
Thumbs.db
[Dd]esktop.ini

# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 7. BUILD ARTIFACTS AND DISTRIBUTION
# ------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Files created when packaging Python projects or building binaries.
develop-eggs/
downloads/
eggs/
build/
dist/
downloads/
/*.zip
/*.tar.gz
